Package farm.core

Class FarmManager

Object
FarmManager
public class FarmManager extends Object
Controller class, coordinating information between the model and view/UI of the program.

The FarmManager file is provided for you, please move it from outside the src into src/farm/core before beginning work on it.
The project won't compile if it is moved into place before Farm is ready.

Whilst a lot of the Manager has been provided to you there are four methods you need to implement to make it work.
Method stubs have been provided to ensure the code compiles and these methods have been made protected.

Whilst the majority of FarmManager is implemented in stage2, the concept of quantities isn't introduced till stage3, at which point the FarmManager will need to be extended.

Only edit the four methods defined in the JavaDoc that aren't tagged as provided, if you touch something else it may break the control loop.
These being: addToInventory(String), addToInventory(String, int), createCustomer(), initiateTransaction(String).

Component of Stage 2.

    • addToInventory

      protected void addToInventory(String productName)
      Adds a single product with corresponding name to the Farm's inventory.

      All the products added should be of regular quality.

      If the product is added successfully display the product add success message ShopFront.displayProductAddSuccess()
      If the provided productName is invalid, that is not 'egg', 'milk', 'wool', or 'jam', display the product add failed message ShopFront.displayProductAddFailed(String) with an appropriately corresponding message.
      If an exception is thrown, display the product add failed message ShopFront.displayProductAddFailed(String) with details of the problem as described in the exception message.

      Parameters:
      productName - the name of the product to add to the farm.
      Hint:
      The correct product names are "egg", "milk", "jam", and "wool"
      Is there something to help you?

    • addToInventory

      protected void addToInventory(String productName, int quantity)
      Adds a certain number of the given product with corresponding name to the Farm's inventory.

      All the products added should be of regular quality.

      If the product is added successfully display the product add success message ShopFront.displayProductAddSuccess().
      If the provided productName is invalid, that is not 'egg', 'milk', 'wool', or 'jam', display the product add failed message ShopFront.displayProductAddFailed(String) with an appropriately corresponding message.
      If an exception is thrown, display the product add failed message ShopFront.displayProductAddFailed(String) with details of the problem as described in the exception message.

      Parameters:
      productName - the name of the product to add to the farm.
      quantity - the amount of the product to add.
      Hint:
      The correct product names are "egg", "milk", "jam", and "wool"
      Is there something to help you?

    • createCustomer

      protected void createCustomer()
      Prompt the user to create a new customer and then save it to the farms address book for later usage.
      A customer needs a name, phone number, and address. See ShopFront.promptForCustomerName(), ShopFront.promptForCustomerNumber(), and ShopFront.promptForCustomerAddress()

      If there is already a customer with the same details display the duplicate customer message. See ShopFront.displayDuplicateCustomer()

      If the phone number entered is not a valid number - that is, contains character that aren't digits such as "123a4" - display the invalid phone number message ShopFront.displayInvalidPhoneNumber()

    • initiateTransaction

      protected void initiateTransaction(String transactionType)
      Start a new transaction for the transaction manager to manage. There are three types of transactions that can be made that correspond to different values being passed in.

      Type to transaction:
        "-s" or "-specialsale" makes a SpecialSaleTransaction
        "-c" or "-categorised" makes a CategorisedTransaction
        anything else as a type makes a Transaction

      Steps to create a transaction in:

      1. Prompt the user for the name of the customer doing the transaction. See ShopFront.promptForCustomerName()
      2. Prompt the user for the customers phone number. See ShopFront.promptForCustomerNumber()
        • If the phone number is invalid - that is, contains character that aren't digits such as "123a4" - display the invalid phone number message and return ShopFront.displayInvalidPhoneNumber()
      3. Look up the customer in the farms address book with those details
        • If there is no corresponding customer with the details display the customer not found message and return ShopFront.displayCustomerNotFound()
      4. Create the appropriate transaction for the type passed in, as defined above, for the customer.
        • If the transaction is SpecialSaleTransaction, prompt the user to get the discounts using getDiscounts()
      5. Display the transaction start message. ShopFront.displayTransactionStart()
      6. Start the actual transaction.
      7. If the transaction fails to start, display the failed to create transaction message ShopFront.displayFailedToCreateTransaction()
      Parameters:
      transactionType - the type of transaction to make
      Hint:
      Be careful to follow the steps in the correct order.
